0.title: Myanmar Admits to Political Prisoners, Pledging Their Freedom
0.summary: The president, on a visit to Britain, Myanmar’s former colonial power, made the unusual guarantee that the country would free political prisoners.

1.title: Petraeus’s Pay for Part-Time CUNY Job, Criticized at $200,000, Drops to $1
1.summary: The university announced David H. Petraeus’s decision to work free as it faces criticism over his compensation and questions over its disclosure.

2.title: Books Of the Times: ‘The Panopticon,’ a Debut Novel by Jenni Fagan
2.summary: “The Panopticon” by Jenni Fagan centers on a fierce 15-year-old who forges bonds with other girls yearning to escape confinement.

3.title: Inquiry Into 787 Fire Said to Focus on Transmitter
3.summary: The emergency transmitter, which would send out the plane’s location in the event of a crash, is powered by a small lithium-manganese battery.

4.title: Leonard Garment, Nixon Lawyer and Watergate Figure, Dies at 89
4.summary: Mr. Garment discouraged Mr. Nixon from destroying White House tapes and pushed unsuccessfully for the president’s early resignation. He also recommended to Gerald R. Ford that Mr. Nixon be pardoned.

5.title: Trailside: Poll Finds Quinn, Weiner and Spitzer Are Out Front
5.summary: A survey of races for New York City mayor and comptroller indicated that scandals might not be weighing down two candidates.

6.title: At White House, Elder Bush Pays Tribute, and Receives It
6.summary: In a homecoming tinged with nostalgia and an unspoken sense of farewell, the elder George Bush joined President Obama at the White House on Monday to present an award for Mr. Bush’s volunteer initiative.

7.title: Jack Handey Is the Envy of Every Comedy Writer in America
7.summary: The man behind “Deep Thoughts” and the quest for the one true joke.

8.title: Egyptian Liberals Embrace the Military, Brooking No Dissent
8.summary: Liberal Egyptians have long had an uneasy relationship with the military, but since it pushed out President Mohamed Morsi, a majority have been intolerant of dissenters.

9.title: D.N.A. Backs Lore on Pre-Columbian Dogs
9.summary: Carolina dogs, like a few other breeds, are without certain genetic markers indicating European origins, suggesting they have been in the Americas since the last Ice Age.

10.title: Saying Senate Is ‘Broken,’ Reid Vows to Limit Filibuster
10.summary: Senator Harry Reid suggested on Monday that Republicans had one way to avoid new curbs on the delaying tactic: give Democrats an up-or-down vote on seven executive branch nominations.

11.title: Court Ruling Deals a Blow to China’s Labor-Camp System
11.summary: A $429 award was an acknowledgment that a woman should not have been sent to a labor camp for demanding harsher punishment for some of the men who raped her daughter.

12.title: Glaxo Used Travel Firms in Bribery, China Says
12.summary: Doctors, hospitals and government officials were allegedly paid off via the travel agencies, the authorities said.

13.title: DealBook: Britain Charges 2 Former Brokers in Libor Inquiry
13.summary: Two former brokers at RP Martin Holdings, Terry J. Farr and James A. Gilmour, were charged with conspiracy to defraud related to an investigation into the manipulation of benchmark interest rates.

14.title: A Secret Surveillance Program Proves Challengeable in Theory Only
14.summary: The Obama administration says criminal defendants may have standing to challenge federal surveillance programs, but try telling that to prosecutors.

15.title: City Room: New York Today: Heat Wave
15.summary: What you need to know to start your Monday: soaring temperatures, protests and arrests in the city over the Zimmerman verdict, and the return of the Twinkie.

16.title: The Appraisal: A Connecticut Estate, With Over $120 Million in Mortgages
16.summary: Copper Beech Farm in Greenwich, on the market for $190 million, has been yoked, through its loans and through its owner, to a tale of the American West.

17.title: At Home Run Derby, the Cheap Seats Are Anything But
17.summary: The Home Run Derby may be the most popular part of baseball’s All-Star festivities, and the most coveted seats for Monday’s event at Citi Field are far from the action.

18.title: Bangladesh Sentences Former Islamic Party Head to 90 Years
18.summary: Ghulam Azam, 91, the former leader of the Jaamat-e-Islami party, was sentenced to 90 years in prison for crimes committed during the country’s 1971 war for independence.

19.title: U.S. Steps Up Public Diplomacy in Egypt Crisis
19.summary: Deputy Secretary of State William J. Burns arrived in Cairo on Monday at a time when both sides of Egypt’s crisis have exhibited strong anti-American sentiment.

20.title: China’s G.D.P. Growth Slows as Government Changes Gears
20.summary: Analysts said China’s notably slower growth in the second quarter of the year demonstrated Beijing’s new commitment to overhauling the economy.

21.title: Bangladesh Sentences Ex-Party Chief to 90 Years
21.summary: A former Islamic party chief in Bangladesh was sentenced to 90 years in jail on Monday for crimes against humanity during the country’s 1971 independence war.

22.title: Snowden Has ‘Blueprints’ to NSA, Journalist Says
22.summary: Edward Snowden has highly sensitive documents on how the National Security Agency is structured and operates that could harm the U.S. government, but has insisted that they not be made public, a journalist close to the NSA leaker said.

23.title: South and North Korea Resume Talks on Reopening Factory Complex
23.summary: Negotiations began again Monday over the jointly operated Kaesong industrial park, a symbol of inter-Korean cooperation that has been closed for months.

-1.title: Metta World Peace Says He Has Deal With Knicks
-1.summary: Metta World Peace confirmed Monday on the MSG Network, during a Knicks summer league game, that he had agreed to a two-year deal with the team.
